{"_id":"q9uywpKzxKMh8J4h","name":"Suricar - Kuboran mercenary","content":"<h3><strong>Suricar – a Kuboran</strong></h3>\n<p>While the experience of most ‘civilised’ men is that Kubora from the deep woods are surly and aggressive Suricar has been in the pay of the Earl for 3 years and has mellowed in his approach to non-Kubora. No doubt he’d still happily cut their throats if he encountered them in the forest but he’s got used to pay and the Earl’s supplies and does not intend to have to run for the forest by behaving stupidly. His primary language is the Old Jarinese dialect spoken by the Kubora but he’s picked up a lot of Harnic during his time in the Earl’s service.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If asked about Coln Kutz …</strong></p>\n<p>Kutz went out of his way to get to know the Kuboran mercenaries and to learn their language – not like most of the southrons or northmen. He was a favoured coedrheg to the tribes and Suricar accompanied him on a couple of trips to the Asawne and Uld Kubora.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">\"Yes.  I know the man called Kutz...one of the few southrons welcome in our tent.  Respects our ways and took the time to learn our way of speaking.  While not of our people, he is a favored <em>coedrheg</em> among many of the tribes.  I, and some of my brothers, have accompanied Kutz into the lands of our Asawne and Uld cousins.\"</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If asked about ‘coedrheg’ ...</strong></p>\n<p>That is the word the Kubora gave to the non-Kubora who picked up some of their ways. They sometimes acted as go betweens or emissaries to the tribes. Coed means ‘trees’ and rheg means ‘run’ in their dialect. They are respectful of Kuboran ways and go out of their way to show they understand they are the inferiors when in the forest. Kutz knew he was an outsider and behaved honourably. In the end he began to realise he didn’t need all the iron many of the mercenaries wear and dressed for the forest.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">\"</span><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">Coed is our word for 'trees' and rheg is 'to run'.  </span><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">It is the name we have given to those like Kutz...those that are 'like but unlike' our people.  Kemlar has seen fit to open their eyes the ways of the Kubora, and Kutz is one of the few that understands he is an outsider...and tries to behave honorably, treading lightly as they move through our lands.  The coedrheg respect the forest, unlike most southrons who stumble through it blindly, with their metal skin (he lets his gaze fall pointedly on any of the party that are heavily armoured), thinking they can bend the trees, the land, and the wind to their will.</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If asked what might have happened to Kutz …</strong></p>\n<p>Maybe he didn’t learn enough - the forest feeds on those who fear it. Rumour is he took a wrong turn and ended up in the marshes where the Ogres will have eaten him. or perhaps...</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">\"</span><span style=\"color:#191813;font-size:18.6667px\">I have not seen Kutz here in many 10-days.  Perhaps he did not learn enough to pass safely across the land.  The forest  feeds on those who fear it.  This is just how it is.  The rumors carried on the wind are that Kutz has allowed the forest lure him into the marshlands, where he and his band were consumed by the <em>anghenfil</em>.  Or, worse yet...</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>At this point Suricar very pointedly shuts up, and breaks his gaze with the PCs...completely shutting down the interaction.  A successful <em><strong>Awareness</strong></em> roll will allow the PCs to gain some insight into what just happened:</p>\n<p>CF:  the PC(s) have no idea what happened.  Suricar has completely ended the interview and they are clueless.  If they attempt to continue the questioning, several of Suricar's friends start closing in on the PCs, fingering knife hilts and handaxes that are stuck through their belts.</p>\n<p>MF:  the PC(s) assume that they have somehow committed a blunder, and are not sure how to recover.</p>\n<p>MS:  The PC(s) are aware that Suricar feels he was about to say more than he intended (or should have).  He stands, nods his head in farewell, and puts his hand to his chest in some sort of sign of respect.</p>\n<p>CS:  In addition being aware of Suricar's state of mind, the PCs also see that while saying farewell, he also takes hold of a carved wooden token that is strung around his neck...and silently mouths something as he does so.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If asked about the token, the marshlands, or anghenfil...</strong></p>\n<p>He has nothing more to say and further probing will result in him looking to his friends. They show themselves ready for a fight if the PCs don’t take the hint and end their questioning.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If the PCs manage to get a look at the token, or somehow convince Suricar to show it to them...</strong></p>\n<p>This is highly unlikely, but allow the PCs to make any reasonable attempt.  If they have been especially respectful, a slight positive modifier may be applied.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.B2s6cQtRVZUGh1iX]{Wooden Token}</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Possible approaches</h2>\n<p>Intrigue:  Kuboran ways are probably foreign to the PCs.  Utilizing Intrique would be a long drawn-out process.</p>\n<p>Oratory:  Normally, Kuborans love story-telling.  If the PCs devote their entire time available, they may be able to work this to their advantage.</p>\n<p>Rhetoric (Command):  if combined with Acting, or the player devises some sort of plan whereby they appear to be high-ranking regular/mercenary, Suricar may momentarily be put off-guard.  Kuborans are highly resistant to outside interference though, so it will need to have elements of firm but respectable requests.</p>\n<p>Rhetoric (Diplomacy):  if combined with an understanding of Kuboran culture/language (either by the PC, or by employing a translator), a successful roll may yeild some results.</p>\n<p>Rhetoric (Intimidation):  Suricar is not receptive to threats.  He has the backing of his closeknit band of warriors, who will menacingly send the PCs on their way.</p>\n<p>Awareness:  if requested by the PC before attempting to interact with Suricar, they may gain some insight.  They can tell that Suricar holds some position of leadership within his tight band of warriors.  They are also aware that he seems familiar with southron speech and social interactions.</p>\n<p>Lovecraft:  the PC will have to devise some sort of reasonable approach.  It would probably require a CS to achieve any sort of positive result.</p>\n<p>Acting:  if utilized by the PC, have them provide some rationale what they are attempting to achieve.  This can either provide a bonus to a further role of another method (i.e., Rhetoric) or the PC can us acting by itself, as long as they devise a plausible plan of how this will help to disclose information.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Speaking with Suricar in Kuboran will provide a +20 modifier in any social interaction attempts.</p>\n<p> </p>","img":null,"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.AWWHCRer9jqh1Y5E","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_zjxyn6q3qdl","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act I:  Into the Forest#/CF_SEP/Clues","color":"#36134e","sort":100000}}}
{"_id":"qce8lYFtIFwvfNzh","name":"07 (Ground Level) The Spirit of Water","content":"<p>This spirit is in a quiescent, vegetative state, mechanically conjuring water into the hole from the watery dimension from which it was summoned. It is this water that permeates the lower levels of the Hand before trickling out into the surrounding jumble of blocks and the Broken Lands beyond. The Spirit was intended to erode the evil beneath the Hand but instead it has become the medium through which that corruption has spread through and beyond the Hand via the red sediment that is carried down to the Marsh and, perhaps, beyond.</p>\n<p>It might be possible to establish a link with the Spirit if a PC had the mental skills or arcane talent of one of a handful of Savoryans across Kethira. However, even if they were successful it has no intelligence with which to say anything.</p>\n<p>The flow of water has been going on for a very long time. <em><strong>Mineralogy</strong></em> will put that timescale at a century or more based on the extent to which the hole in the base of the bowl in the floor has begun to occlude.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.kBS7CqKxhYEqoUnl","hash":"7fde535a2b5ab298b316c7b3f7b58652c8717b11"},"cf":{"id":"temp_rsvekvf6s4","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act VI:  The Hand of Crador#/CF_SEP/Map Key - locations","color":"#000000","sort":800000}}}
{"_id":"qjRv92wMOdu91dBp","name":"01 - Ground Floor - Common Room","content":"<h2>Common Room</h2>\n<p>The White Stoat’s Common Room is a large and well lit room with space for 10 customers to sit comfortably. Visitors will rarely, if ever, see it that busy and will probably wonder how the Stoat stays in business. During the night Jamys’ business associates sleep here near the fire or, if they wish to be more discrete, in the bunks in the attic.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>The door to the small Snug Bar that occupies one corner of the Common Room is always open unless Jamys is in conference. However it may as well be a locked castle gate as it is Jamys’s professional domain and none enter here without his express invitation. Whenever he is here there are two well-built young men present. They spend their time playing dice but are always seated so they can see what anyone talking to Jamys is doing. Both minders have stout clubs and knives beneath their jerkins and will intervene if Jamys appears to be in any physical danger. If necessary the entire inn staff will descend on anyone threatening Jamys. They all value their places here and have much to lose if anything happened to him.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.actors.bL1RtVhXQl8zW1kS]{Jamys of Abrant}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.actors.nMnuLSAwDFlDhiXe]{Minder 1 - Nath of Rysten}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.actors.psivNB5Kg9WRsNA0]{Minder 2 - Merwas of Chornic}</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.RmVvVTrkM8hrmsWm]{The White Stoat Inn - GM Map}</p>","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/scenes/Heart_of_Darkness/White_Stoat_Inn_GM_Map.PNG","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.QjPNF0dLLEX7r3oY","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_b8slu2n3iw","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/The White Stoat Inn","color":"#212121","sort":1000000}}}
{"_id":"qoPzsKiwMf31aA7i","name":"Top of the Cataract","content":"","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/scenes/Heart_of_Darkness/TopOfTheCataract.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Pu1a5JcgTQAjoaYt","hash":"a5b9974eab806b62d2e8d1844acc5b4ae3393e48"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3t0858bnqro","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act III:  Further Upstream","color":"#4f86b0","sort":925000}}}
{"_id":"qskotkT1tx8MDhxr","name":"Spirit of the Air","content":"<p> </p>\n<h3><strong>The Spirit of Air</strong></h3>\n<p>The remorseless competition between the Yelgri and the chaotic, vibrant life of the colony is one reason why the Spirit of Air has slowly crept back towards consciousness over the last century. The Spirit has no clear recollection of how long it has been here, but assumes it is a long time. Equally it has no recollection of who, or what, bound it here, but knows that it was for an important reason – to help keep something contained or protected.</p>\n<p>The spirit’s capacity to influence the environment around its eerie declines very quickly with increased distance from its ‘binding rune’. Within the small cavern it is at almost the full physical strength of its prime. This is why its cave remains clean and undisturbed. It has kept out any bird that has sought to nest in the cave and a wall of pressure that keeps the Harpies out.</p>\n<p>While its physical strength declines quickly away from the cave its senses have awoken to almost full strength and its perceptions stretch out from the cave as far as the boundary of the Hand and down into the air spaces between the limestone pillars. If the PCs scale one of the pillars seeking entry to the Hand it will sense their presence as the only genuinely intelligent creatures it remembers ever encountering. In an effort to attract their attention it will seek to buffet a passing Yelgri in a way that any PC with <em><strong>Weatherlore</strong></em> will instantly see as curiously unnatural. It will sense their attention and then move any Yelgri coming close enough in increasingly unnatural ways to confirm in the PCs mind that there may be something in or around the cave that is worth investigation.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.actors.7PK1dmEBQQatljoO]{Spirit of the Air}</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>The Spirit's <em><strong>Push</strong></em> skill can be used in a variety of ways:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>buffet the Yelgri(s) in-flight if they approach too close to the cave</li>\n<li>destroy anything that the PCs might build or put-together to help them climb one of the Hand's fingers</li>\n<li>blow a PC off their feet...and potentially off the top of the Hand, opposed by STR x 5 if target manages to find something solid to grab onto</li>\n<li>destroy inanimate objects by crushing them or bursting through them</li>\n<li>support a character in the air, if it succeeds vs. (average of STR+STA) x 5</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<p>In combat, the Spirit can either use <em><strong>Push</strong></em> to keep opponents off-balance and away from the cave, or it can use <em><strong>Bludgeon</strong></em> to cause physical damage.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>The Spirit should not be immediately hostile.  It is more curious at first and will use suble hints to see how the PCs will react.  The PCs actions will determine if the Spirit tries to lure the PCs closer in an attempt to learn more (and possible communicate) or if the Spirit loses interest in the PCs and simply acts to keep them away from its cave.</p>\n<p>The reason the Spirit wants to ‘meet’ the PCs is that with its slow emergence into consciousness it has sensed changes in the environment below. It has come to believe that it is not the only Spirit bound to the Hand but despite its efforts to call out to the others it is receiving only confused, animalistic responses. If it could ‘speak’ to the PCs it would ask them to seek out the other spirits and report back their state for it feels it should be concerned for their well-being.</p>\n<p>The Spirit is unable to communicate with the PCs in any normal way but can draw very precise pictures in the limestone dust it can scour from the walls of its chamber.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/actors/NPCs/Heart%20of%20Darkness/Ardo%20of%20Guil%20v2.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.swJgQlldeS78UV0R","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_m4r2k8xc6l","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act VI:  The Hand of Crador","color":"#886c44","sort":825000}}}
