{"_id":"wV3Vh4ZpniG0pHAS","name":"Holding Breath and Drowning","content":"<p>The Roper Snake will attempt to hold any successfully grappled opponent underwater with one of its tails until that person passes out and drowns.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Characters can hold their breath for Endurance × 10 seconds, but they accumulate 1 point of Fatigue for each 2 consecutive (10-second) rounds they are held underwater by the snake's tail.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Fatigue Levels are recovered at a rate of one level per 10 minutes of rest.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>A character who spends more (consecutive) time underwater than they can hold their breath passes out, the character’s lungs fill with water, they stop breathing, and the character will die in Endurance×20 seconds unless revived.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.b18ty1tXmXN6NdHR","hash":"608fd1ec58037facdcd3a682dd67e3caaaa539fa"},"cf":{"id":"temp_l6pmdy1m8b9","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Game Mechanics","color":"#bb47bd"}}}
{"_id":"x1muSTLG1BODw2vG","name":"01 - The Attic - Sleeping Chambers","content":"<h2>Justi and Donara's Chamber</h2>\n<p>This attic room is shared by Justi and Donara, though one of them is usually to be found with Jamys.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Guildsmen Bunks</h2>\n<p>The bunks at the far end of the attic serve as discrete quarters for his guildsmen when it is best they aren’t seen in the common room.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.RmVvVTrkM8hrmsWm]{The White Stoat Inn - GM Map}</p>","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/scenes/Heart_of_Darkness/White_Stoat_Inn_GM_Map.PNG","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.utLKWvUNsJCXBPos","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_b8slu2n3iw","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/The White Stoat Inn","color":"#212121","sort":1300000}}}
{"_id":"xj0HYDXfen5cfGGV","name":"Asawne Kubora:  Credits","content":"<p>This work (see list of Foundry Journal entries below) is derived from the PDF \"ASAWNE KUBORA\" from Lythia.com (<a title=\"Asawne Kubora\" href=\"https://www.lythia.com/harnworld/people-cultures/asawne_kubora/\">https://www.lythia.com/harnworld/people-cultures/asawne_kubora/</a>), and has been adapted to Foundry VTT by Michael Gurley.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Writer: </strong>Alun Rees</p>\n<p><strong>Maps:</strong> Alun Rees</p>\n<p><strong>Contributors:</strong> Dan Bell, Neil Thompson,  and the playtesters at HarnCon8 and IviniaCon 2</p>\n<p><strong>Thanks:</strong> N. Robin Crossby and Columbia Games for Hârn.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.Frd976O44QA6fYOy]{Asawne Kubora: Origins &amp; History}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.PwHbcye3WDKJ0Zbf]{Asawne Kubora: The Asawne Clans}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.cVG5q4YAPHYoDuI7]{Asawne Kubora: The Warband of Clan Gomas}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.QPMHhbXCFMaj7kSM]{Asawne Kubora: Kuboran Honour}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.QFpdl18gZUPd0KAh]{Asawne Kubora: The Worship of Heneryne}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.KAXPUy2dEyzlpxPl]{Asawne Kubora: The Worship of Crador}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.pPjKVztF3deOsDFj]{Asawne Kubora: Disturbing News}</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.WjOTwMxPFCvjwn1f]{Clan Gomas: Village}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.ZkC6fUcji0ASmwVk]{01 Village - Cattle Grazing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.W1YTsQuokS5qcMbZ]{02 Village - Hogs Copse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.FTcWj1h9Q6onUJhh]{03 Village - Heneryne's Glade}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.YgWgtFVxSG4jZdgs]{04 Village - Hunter's Path}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.8HtCqweAEpTN8lAu]{05a Village - Stranger's Beach}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.dli8avGRTzWDLE80]{05b Village - Trading Post}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.LxyHeNGIzc3vnmEx]{05c Village - Shuntul Lodge}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.jnNIZurfQllcmYEG]{05d Village - Hunuhn's Round-house}</p>","img":null,"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.vFDuySKD2wAVyAVF","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0b2m4o5az66m","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Asawne Kubora","color":"#1723c4","sort":750000}}}
{"_id":"y8TCpD3q2dLrMqIn","name":"13 (Lower Level) Confronting Kutz","content":"<p><strong>The PCs have several possible courses of action...</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Walk away – the hope has to be that the PCs tribulations to date will make this inconceivable. As an incentive, if the PCs do leave without Kutz they should find the Spirit of Earth outside the chamber waiting for them. It will drive them back into the passage to the Chamber but will not advance.</li>\n<li>Kill Kutz where he stands – this would fit within their terms of reference but has consequences (see below) and they still have to get at least his head out as proof.  There is at least a hope that if they could free him from the Heart he could walk out under his own power.  @Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.nkRbZ1NpL9ocqeaS]{13 (Lower Level) Confronting The Heart}</li>\n<li>Wrestle him free from the column – grappling the body of Kutz while he seeks to destroy the Heart with his broken sword is not difficult but no matter what strength the PCs bring to bare (and 3 of them can gain a hold on him at any one time) they will make no progress.  His hand is not simply resting on the block but been merged with it, his flesh being consumed alongside his spirit by the Heart.</li>\n<li>Cut him free of the Block by severing his forearm - this is allowed within their terms of reference. The target is inert and his forearm does not yet have the resilience to damage of the limestone or the Heart within so it will not be difficult to achieve this with an edged weapon. A PC should be allowed to strike the arm below the point at which it has begun to atrophy to stone unless they CF. If they aim higher and take his arm off above the elbow then he will need rapid medical attention if he is not to bleed to death.  @Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.nkRbZ1NpL9ocqeaS]{13 (Lower Level) Confronting The Heart}</li>\n<li>Attack the Heart themselves – they can attempt this but looking at the progress Kutz has made they might judge this an unlikely route to success. They would be right in this judgement. The other half of his sword blade lies at his feet (Weaponcraft will show it to be of good quality).  While he has successfully hacked a deep notch in the limestone it is making no impression on the beating Heart within. The Heart should be considered immune to physical attack, even if its coat of limestone and atrophied bodies could be prized away from it. However any attack on it will raise its awareness of the PCs.  @Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.nkRbZ1NpL9ocqeaS]{13 (Lower Level) Confronting The Heart}</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It would be better for subsequent adventures in this series if Kutz can be brought from the Hand alive.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>If the PCs either:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>attack the limestone column;</strong></li>\n<li><strong>add their attacks to the notch Kutz has already cut;</strong></li>\n<li><strong>kill Kutz;</strong></li>\n<li><strong>severe his left arm to free him; or</strong></li>\n<li><strong>deliberately touch the stalagmite or seek to make mental contact of any kind with what beats within...</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Heart will become aware of them. Its attention is not something to encourage as once its attention is drawn to the PCs it will begin to exert its influence on them, pulsing more rapidly as it does so.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.journals.nkRbZ1NpL9ocqeaS]{13 (Lower Level) Confronting The Heart}</p>","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/actors/NPCs/Heart%20of%20Darkness/Coln_of_Kutz.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.67emwwS84lUukFA9"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.TLDxdgpYgjWixCnV","hash":"a1158ffa923d5ba7a0710c23cea6c7dc405fe410"},"cf":{"id":"temp_rsvekvf6s4","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act VI:  The Hand of Crador#/CF_SEP/Map Key - locations","color":"#000000","sort":1700000}}}
{"_id":"yeR4WZjCbhxSuRe8","name":"Hole - C6","content":"<p>Some of the spaces encountered within the Hand of Crador constitute a significant physical danger as they are not only open to the sky above but also open into the spaces below. All such holes in the floor lead to a drop indicated on the maps.</p>\n<p>Those marked [**] have no easy ledge around them.  PCs can use <em><strong>Jumping</strong></em> (a standing jump as there is never a sufficiently straight run up to make a running leap practical) or <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> to make their way from entry to exit without falling into the lower level.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Climbing</h2>\n<p> </p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1549%;height:68px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:29.2716%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>SECTION</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:32.6446%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>RATING</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:37.2314%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>DISTANCE</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.2716%\">Vertical Climb</td>\n<td style=\"width:32.6446%;text-align:center\">Easy</td>\n<td style=\"width:37.2314%;text-align:center\">32 feet</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Progress per <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> skill roll is measured in feet.  Negative progress indicates that the character has encountered an obstacle and forced to backtrack.  A running total of progress is kept to determine when the climb is complete, and the extent of any fall.</p>\n<p>If the character(s) have good climbing gear (rope, grappling hooks, hammer/pitons, etc.) and/or they come up with clever ideas to increase their chances for success, the GM may grant a <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> EML increase as they see fit.</p>\n<p>If the characters have rope, and wish to use it to assist in either a vertical descent or to protect an traversing climber, 6' of the rope will be used per person acting as an anchor, or 6-24' (1d4 x 6') will be required to tie the rope off to some (solid?) rock feature in the passageway.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<table style=\"width:98.8611%;height:114px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\"><strong>Success</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\"><strong>Easy</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\"><strong>Hard</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\"><strong>Very Hard</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">CS</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">+30'</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">+20'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">+10'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">MS</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">+15'</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">+10'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">+5'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">MF</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">0</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">-5'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">-10'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">CF</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Falling</h2>\n<p>Any fall of more than five feet inflicts a blunt strike.  Strike location is randomly determined, usually on the Body (Mid on Aiming Zone table).</p>\n<p><strong>Depth:  32 feet</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">HEIGHT (in feet)</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">SURFACE</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">INJURY DICE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">31-40</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">deep water</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">2d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">21-30</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">deep water</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">1d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">11-20</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">deep water</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">none</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">6-10</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">deep water</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">none</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">0-5 feet</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">deep water</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">none</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>In a clear fall of more than 15 feet, <em><strong>Acrobatics</strong></em> or <em><strong>Dodge</strong></em> can be used to moderate the fall, by landing on one's feet rather than one's head.</p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%;height:51px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\"><strong>Skill</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>CF</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>MF</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>MS</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>CS</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\">Acrobatics</td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\">n/a</td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-2d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-3d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\">Dodge</td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+2d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-2d6</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Grabbing</h2>\n<p>A character may be able to stop falling by grabbing protrusions, bushes, etc.  This rarely stops the fall, but may slow it and reduce landing impact.  Success is determined by testing <em><strong>DEXx5</strong></em>.</p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">ROLL</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">DESCRIPTION</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">RESULT</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">CS</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Fall slowed</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Impact Reduced by 3d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">MS</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Fall slowed</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Impact Reduced by 2d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">MF</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">No effect</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">No change to fall damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">CF</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Character has wrenched one or both arms.</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Blunt Minor Injury (M1) in-addition to the normal fall damage.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>If a grabbing attempt reduces the impact of the fall below ZERO, the grab has succeeded.  The character now hangs from the protrusion.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Combat</h2>\n<p>Combat in these open areas <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">that contain holes in the floor</span> have the following constraints:</p>\n<p>If the PCs are in a passageway  that emerges into the open area, 2 Gargun can engage 1 PC.</p>\n<p>If the PCs are able to force their way into the open area, 3 Gargun can engage 1 PC.</p>\n<p>A <em><strong>STUMBLE</strong></em> result during combat results in the combatant falling into the hole.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.mN3BLeFNQ5WGQl9w"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.fdtfkQIzTltuPrwv","hash":"5f64a1bc3bcdb3e0b75aa3c72621ba153b83f855"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vvq6w10rbuj","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act VI:  The Hand of Crador#/CF_SEP/Map Key - vertical passages","color":"#000000","sort":1300000}}}
{"_id":"yoxKeADI3IgvmO3S","name":"Hole - C1","content":"<p>Some of the spaces encountered within the Hand of Crador constitute a significant physical danger as they are not only open to the sky above but also open into the spaces below. All such holes in the floor lead to a drop indicated on the maps.</p>\n<p>Those marked [**] have no easy ledge around them.  PCs can use <em><strong>Jumping</strong></em> (a standing jump as there is never a sufficiently straight run up to make a running leap practical) or <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> to make their way from entry to exit without falling into the lower level.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Climbing</h2>\n<p> </p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1549%;height:68px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:29.2716%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>SECTION</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:32.6446%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>RATING</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:37.2314%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>DISTANCE</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.2716%\">Vertical Climb</td>\n<td style=\"width:32.6446%;text-align:center\">Easy</td>\n<td style=\"width:37.2314%;text-align:center\">36 feet</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Progress per <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> skill roll is measured in feet.  Negative progress indicates that the character has encountered an obstacle and forced to backtrack.  A running total of progress is kept to determine when the climb is complete, and the extent of any fall.</p>\n<p>If the character(s) have good climbing gear (rope, grappling hooks, hammer/pitons, etc.) and/or they come up with clever ideas to increase their chances for success, the GM may grant a <em><strong>Climbing</strong></em> EML increase as they see fit.</p>\n<p>If the characters have rope, and wish to use it to assist in either a vertical descent or to protect an traversing climber, 6' of the rope will be used per person acting as an anchor, or 6-24' (1d4 x 6') will be required to tie the rope off to some (solid?) rock feature in the passageway.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<table style=\"width:98.8611%;height:114px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\"><strong>Success</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\"><strong>Easy</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\"><strong>Hard</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\"><strong>Very Hard</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">CS</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">+30'</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">+20'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">+10'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">MS</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">+15'</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">+10'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">+5'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">MF</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">0</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">-5'</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">-10'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.139%;text-align:center\">CF</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.8774%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n<td style=\"width:25.7309%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2497%;text-align:center\">Fall</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Falling</h2>\n<p>Any fall of more than five feet inflicts a blunt strike.  Strike location is randomly determined, usually on the Body (Mid on Aiming Zone table).</p>\n<p><strong>Depth:  36 feet</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">HEIGHT (in feet)</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">SURFACE</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">INJURY DICE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">31-40</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">limestone</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">5d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">21-30</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">limestone</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">4d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">11-20</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">limestone</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">3d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">6-10</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">limestone</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">2d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26.4992%\">0-5 feet</td>\n<td style=\"width:31.5507%\">limestone</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.0905%\">none</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>In a clear fall of more than 15 feet, <em><strong>Acrobatics</strong></em> or <em><strong>Dodge</strong></em> can be used to moderate the fall, by landing on one's feet rather than one's head.</p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%;height:51px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\"><strong>Skill</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>CF</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>MF</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>MS</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\"><strong>CS</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\">Acrobatics</td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\">n/a</td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-2d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-3d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:18.0208%;height:17px\">Dodge</td>\n<td style=\"width:18.7615%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+2d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:20.2066%;text-align:center;height:17px\">+1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:22.8077%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-1d6</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.0572%;text-align:center;height:17px\">-2d6</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Grabbing</h2>\n<p>A character may be able to stop falling by grabbing protrusions, bushes, etc.  This rarely stops the fall, but may slow it and reduce landing impact.  Success is determined by testing <em><strong>DEXx5</strong></em>.</p>\n<table style=\"width:99.1477%\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">ROLL</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">DESCRIPTION</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">RESULT</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">CS</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Fall slowed</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Impact Reduced by 3d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">MS</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Fall slowed</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Impact Reduced by 2d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">MF</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">No effect</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">No change to fall damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:18.0207%\">CF</td>\n<td style=\"width:26.1078%\">Character has wrenched one or both arms.</td>\n<td style=\"width:55.0118%\">Blunt Minor Injury (M1) in-addition to the normal fall damage.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>If a grabbing attempt reduces the impact of the fall below ZERO, the grab has succeeded.  The character now hangs from the protrusion.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Combat</h2>\n<p>Combat in these open areas <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">that contain holes in the floor</span> have the following constraints:</p>\n<p>If the PCs are in a passageway  that emerges into the open area, 2 Gargun can engage 1 PC.</p>\n<p>If the PCs are able to force their way into the open area, 3 Gargun can engage 1 PC.</p>\n<p>A <em><strong>STUMBLE</strong></em> result during combat results in the combatant falling into the hole.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.o3wshhrmquV9iTiV"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.KjECtR0ehIG66NMq","hash":"9ed91bb09b4d8f4fe190ae3f8bcbbc8d71a1be8d"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vvq6w10rbuj","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act VI:  The Hand of Crador#/CF_SEP/Map Key - vertical passages","color":"#000000","sort":1000000}}}
{"_id":"zfitJFLyBY1m4GSe","name":"Gedis: the lost boy","content":"","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/actors/NPCs/Heart%20of%20Darkness/Gedis%20the%20Lost%20Boy_portrait.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.15rAuDcErec9oBqn","hash":"4cd99e3d077bb22962a96216b272647c69c0a4ad"},"cf":{"id":"temp_3t0858bnqro","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Act III:  Further Upstream","color":"#4f86b0","sort":500000}}}
{"_id":"zrNtDlS4b9Tt5pAb","name":"Denal Tenau ('Shaman')","content":"<p>The tenau is the polar opposite of the anghenfil. At the time his massive brother seems to halt his mental development that of the tenau accelerates. Many have memorised all the tales of the Denal by the time they are 10 and mastered the more intricate crafts practiced among their people, including that of the ‘string drum’, soon afterwards. Their hair is never thick as a child and Denal mothers say they can identify how wise their child will be by the age at which their remaining hair recedes and is lost. It is not surprising that they are often identified as a potential shaman early in their life. Though others do not know it almost every tenau has some shaman skills and these are as important in defence of their villages as the strength of the anghenfil.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[heart-of-darkness.actors.56SZoQYVSn7h4y1t]{Denal Tenau (generic)}</p>\n<p>Tenau have a perverse relationship with Crador in as much as though he is thought responsible for their condition, he is also particularly responsive to their calls for help. Hence tenau casting ritual invocations in Crador’s name treat those invocations as if they were one circle less difficult. Invocations cast in Kemlar’s name are one circle more difficult, reflecting the Denal view that he has abandoned them.</p>","img":"modules/heart-of-darkness/image_library/actors/NPCs/Heart%20of%20Darkness/Denal_Tenau.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"x7bG2mHcyINoyNtL":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ao9kCFAo8KX2xDOu","hash":"48bfdaa31d679b437f2f05b653ec46d552d71988"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-adv-sos.journals.6iSsBhoexD6IAIlE"},"undefined":{"hash":"16f413505994ea0d58ec944bd54d63f292d834cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_zqjgdvunkh","path":"Heart of Darkness#/CF_SEP/Denal Kubora","color":"#6e4307","sort":500000}}}
